reviews.text:
Utterly fantastic Chinese takeout. We ordered 4 dishes: shredded pork with garlic sauce, happy family, Singapore mai fun and butterfly shrimp with bacon. They gave us a free quart of wonton soup with the order. The wontons were thick with a good filling and held together well. 
Butterfly shrimp with bacon is an old school Shanghai delicacy that I can rarely find anymore. It was juicy and flavorful. 
The Singapore mai fun was some of the best I've had, with lots of chicken and seafood added. Same with the happy family, lots of beef, pork shrimp chicken and seafood to be had in this dish. 
The standout piece was the shredded pork with garlic sauce. Just the right amount of spice was added,  with some nice heat. The pork was tender and tasty. 
Place inside was clean, staff was very friendly.

They delivered me food when I called 10 minutes prior to then closing! The food was one of the bests that I have had, too. I will definitely be ordering again, just at an earlier time for sure! Thank you China One!

This football season has been nice for me. The Eagles have been doing well. Knocking on wood, my fantasy teams have been also doing well. I also discovered China One as I looked for the Chinese restaurant that opened the earliest on a Sunday right before spending an afternoon *gasp* away from watching football. 

Since then, China One has been my go to spot before those 1:00 games. An odd choice, but it hits the spot to keep me from getting myself sick by overeating pizza and wings. The Eagles also are 3-0 on days where I ate at China One!

The Wonton soup is the best around. The pint is only $1.85, and it has 4-5 MASSIVE and delicious dumpings swimming inside.  I go the literal extra mile to order here rather than China Express because of this. The order is always done within 10 minutes, the staff is friendly, and the price is right.

reviews.text: This place is so good! I found out about it through a girl that works there, Jamie. I got the vegan veggie fajitas and they were seriously the best fajitas I've ever had. The place is so cute and the service was so great! This place is my new lunch spot.

Nice little spot away form busy streets and people.  Had a great vegan bean and rice with vegetables wrapped in a black corn soft wrap.  Very nice.  Side whole food and vegetable salad was perfect size and tasty.

I have been coming here for about 3 years and it is always such a pleasure! Vegan options are in abundance at Cafe Con Leche and I am so grateful for that! Enjoy the many options that are offered at this restaurant. They have options for nonvegans and they also have desserts and coffee.

reviews.text:
This is the most convenient Panera for me but if I could I would choose another location. The staff always seems put off and it does not put me in the mood to splurge on that .99 cent cookie!
The seating area is pretty clean. But it is always hard to find a seat during their rush times.

I generally do not like going to places such as Panera or Dunkin Donuts or really anywhere with customer service where they do not train their employees to be polite and kind, and generally to have a good attitude, but when I went here it was different. The woman who took care of me was extremely nice and kind I wish I remembered her name. It made me hopeful to come back again. that is all.

Was charged 8 times for the same purchase.  Called and spoke with Troy who stated he was the manager.  Troy said they had a problem with a power outage and he thinks that is why the extra charges were incurred.  Will update review once and if resolution has been reached.

reviews.text: 3rd time there still cold coffee and warm not hot breakfast sandwich. 3 strike your out not going back

I was really excited when I heard that is Panera was going in, as I've had issues with the Panera in Lawrence Park Shopping Center, and the Panera in Springfield has a heinous parking lot. I have to say, they always forget my croutons for my Tomato soup, but then again, so do all of the others. The thing that I LOVE the best about this Panera is the fact that there's a manager expediting the food at the counter on the customer waiting side. This may not seem like a big deal, but I hate when the customers are all grouped up trying to figure out, "is this my sandwich, or is this yours?" The employees sometimes say your name so quickly, you're luckily if you get a hint of it at all. I really give them props for this and will continue to choose this location over the others!

Went around 7am to this location to get a bagel was not crowded at all. There was a customer waiting for his order a dozen of bagels I believe. I counted 4 employees working only one cashier though she was picking the bagels and cutting them. the other workers were in back area I saw the manager and made eye contact with her a couple times hoping she would wait on but she was busy talking to another girl. I waited about 5 minutes to finally place my order. After you order you have to go to back to get order which I will say this was rather quick. I asked for a toasted bagel with cream cheese bagel was barely toasted cream cheese was in a small container which was a brand I never heard of was horrible. I usually go to Manhattan bagel a couple stores up but was very crowded. Thought I could save time and go to panera but probably spent same amount of time for a far inferior product.

name: Popeyes Louisiana Kitchen
description: Fast Food, American (Traditional), Food, Chicken Shop, Chicken Wings, Desserts, Restaurants

reviews.text:
This Popeye's Chicken shack sits in a long commercial strip on Trenton Road, Morrisville, Pa.  It is a standard franchise for the company.  The space is clean and attractive, with a well hidden drive thru component around to the back.  

I went in the other evening for a light dinner and to help nourish my life long Southern Fried Chicken addiction. I just can't seem to get enough.  Love the crunch and the hot oil burning my fingers. Love the spicy coat.  Love the way it pulls away from the bone with a little coaxing. 

These days, fried chicken is offered on the more sophisticated menus, and even for breakfast with waffles for those who just want max carb load.  (I'm not there yet.)  But, just because someone with a chef's hat and culinary school degree puts a batch together doesn't mean it is any better than the cheaper, faster, mass produced variety.  In fact, there is a school of thought that fried chicken is like singing the blues.  You know; "You have to suffer if you want to sing the blues..." Those hands playing six string acoustic or even Lucille, bring something to the experience that can be felt deep in the soul.  

Chicken be that way, too.  The true fried chicken artists, like the best Delta or Hills Blues guitarists and singers, are rooted in a culture and existential angst that generates the creative instinct leading to emotionally charged performances.  Those same forces are at work with fried chicken.  In the hands of a master, the chicken becomes an extension of his life, the same way a great song emerges from that primordial place deep in the heart.

This 2 piece box o' chicken may not have been epic, but it was solid and even inspired this review.  So, even though we weren't sitting in Muscle Shoals, Alabama in a roadside chicken house, there was enough there to let the imagination run wild.

Just wish they actually played that music at Popeye's, rather than the current soundtrack.

My better half was craving southern-style chicken tenders and biscuits. Reviews for this Popeyes location were good so took a detour on the way home to pick up the food order.

Prior reviews mentioned that this was a clean location and this is very apparent when one steps into this joint. The interiors are super clean and well maintained (including the rest rooms). 

The chicken tenders were freshly prepared and the last time we had memorably good ones from a fast food spot was at a service area at 5AM (was the first batch). The side of blackened ranch was zesty and paired well with the crispy and spicy tenders. Hit the sweet spot for us and left us feeling so satisfied. Would definitely come back here in the future. Very friendly customer service.

They served me fries in a loose bag wtf is this five guys? The owner must be cheap af my sprite was more like a medium ice with a splash of soda. Fitting that the speaker for the drive thru is next to the trash because that describes this place. I've tried the spicy chicken sandwich at different locations and I can say the one I got is wasn't fresh at all and was overly greasy. This place needs new management ASAP

reviews.text:
First, I believe the owners of the establishment are Korean-Americans (I know that Asians may look alike, but it is ridiculous to believe the account of some of these reviews if you are going into an Asian-style restaurant and ignorantly conglomerate them all as Japanese).

I went on a nice breezy Friday night and found the waitresses to be very helpful. They were quick to seat my party and gave us our time to look through the menu until we were comfortable to order.

I loved the volcano roll and found the miso soup to be one of the best I've had in Philadelphia (and as an Asian, miso soup tells a lot about the quality of what's to come). The waitresses did not hesitate to clear out trays when they were empty, and they always did so politely.

We lingered for a bit after finishing our food and the waitresses did not rush us although it was a a weekend night. I left a nice tip for good food and good service with good friends.

I really like this place.  I eat here about twice a month, I like it that much.  It _is_ slightly generic at first, but the owners run the restaurant and they're super-friendly.  The food is great, and the prices aren't that bad -- I have yet to find another place in Philly that comes close to the quality and the price.  I spent $60 for two and left stuffed.  True, places in Cherry Hill are cheaper, but I'm not about to go all the way there, and then spend $3 on tolls just to get back.

Some people mention Koi (a sushi place down the street) as a better place, but I disagree.  Koi's rolls are very good, but much smaller and more expensive.  I spent $80 there for 2 and left hungry.

One thing about Hikari that I appreciate is they throw in some freebies because they appreciate the business.  Last time, they gave us two pieces of a maki version of "ham and cheese sandwich" -- uncooked salmon and cooked egg with cucumber wrapped in seaweed with rice on the outside to replace the bread.  It was clever and delicious.  I also recommend their udon.  It's the best in town, even better than my mom's.

I really think more people should give this place a try.  For sure it's standard sushi, but I think you get your money's worth if you stick with the rolls.

Really wanted sushi and with few options around I ordered take out from here. The website didn't have prices and I ended up ordering two rolls and an order of edamame. $36! Insanely over priced. Sushi was okay, nothing to write home about.
